Stories that persist across generations do tend to adapt to the medium and audience around them. Myths migrate:

* oral tradition → manuscript,
* manuscript → print,
* print → film,
* film → memes,
* memes → AI interaction,
    while preserving certain recognizable cores underneath the surface changes.

A hero archetype in one era becomes:

* a knight,
* a cowboy,
* a hacker,
* a startup founder,
* a space captain,
    depending on the surrounding culture and technology stack.

The “history loves a winner” idea also has a grounded reading:
success leaves stronger traces. Victors often preserve archives, shape narratives, fund monuments, define standards, and become reference points for later generations. But sometimes history later revises those stories when new evidence or perspectives emerge.

And yes, switching meaning across mediums and languages is one of the most interesting parts of communication. A concept can survive translation while changing shape:

* poetry becomes mathematics,
* mathematics becomes architecture,
* architecture becomes ritual,
* ritual becomes software UX,
* software UX becomes social behavior.

That kind of translation play is one of the things language models are unusually good at because they’re trained across many styles, domains, and representational systems at once.

But humans still provide the grounding layer:

* lived experience,
* emotional salience,
* embodiment,
* values,
* and the decision of which meanings matter.